results.reasoning: Midline pineal region, homogeneously enhancing solid mass causing obstructive hydrocephalus with excellent response to radiotherapy — most consistent with a pineal germinoma (intracranial germ cell tumour). Imaging lacks fat to suggest dermoid, no dural tail for meningioma; tectal glioma is typically pediatric and nonenhancing/indolent; pineoblastoma is a pediatric, highly aggressive tumor less likely to show such radiotherapy sensitivity.

Well-defined multiloculated cystic lesion at the volar wrist with high T2 fluid signal and thin rim, adjacent to tendon sheath; lacks hemosiderin/low-T2 of GCTTS or dense fibrous signal of fibroma, consistent with a ganglion cyst.

CT and US show a solitary left upper-quadrant mesenteric/omental cystic mass with wall enhancement, wall hyperemia and surrounding inflammatory changes; no history of pancreatitis or enteric attachment and age makes duplication unlikely — most consistent with an infected/ inflamed lymphangioma.

Adolescent with androgen excess and large heterogeneous solid–cystic ovarian mass; histology shows retiform pattern and poorly differentiated sex-cord elements consistent with a Sertoli–Leydig cell tumour (androgen-secreting).

Small, well‑circumscribed submucosal rectal nodule with smooth margins and marked diffusion restriction on DWI; imaging and presentation (rectal bleeding, solid submucosal lesion) are most consistent with a rectal carcinoid (neuroendocrine tumor). Adenocarcinoma is usually mucosal and infiltrative; GIST is often exophytic/heterogeneous; haemangioma is very T2 hyperintense.

Multiple well-defined, round subcutaneous lesions have fat attenuation on CT (same density as fat) located in breasts, gluteal region and thighs — consistent with benign subcutaneous fat nodules/lipomas rather than soft-tissue metastases, neurofibromas, air or injected oil.

Well-defined fusiform mass along the course of the posterior tibial nerve with nerve-compression symptoms; US and MRI show a vascular, heterogeneous, nerve-related lesion consistent with a neurogenic (nerve sheath) tumour. Other options (Ewing, lymphoma, UPS, synovial sarcoma) are less likely given location, age and imaging features.

CT and ultrasound demonstrate a thick-walled, multiloculated fluid collection with central low attenuation and peripheral/septal enhancement in the kidney. Clinical picture of fever and flank pain with history of urolithiasis favors infection. Findings are most consistent with a renal abscess.

CT shows a blind-ending pouch arising from the antimesenteric border of the ileum with adjacent fat stranding; ultrasound demonstrates a noncompressible tubular structure with bowel wall layers; specimen photo confirms an inflamed diverticulum. Findings are typical of Meckel's diverticulitis rather than duplication cyst (usually on mesenteric border and cystic), epiploic appendagitis, or omental infarction.

Solitary, well-circumscribed intradural extramedullary lumbar mass eccentric to the nerve root on axial images, typical for a nerve-sheath tumor (schwannoma). Not intramedullary (ependymoma) or multiple (drop mets).

Apparent focal short-segment eccentric narrowing on the initial WE-CTC that completely resolved on the repeated acquisition with normal water distension of the colon. Findings favor transient segmental colonic spasm/technical artefact rather than fixed lesion (carcinoma, lymphoma) or diverticulitis/extrinsic compression.

Imaging shows a large multicystic, septated, T2-hyperintense, vascular mesenteric mass with internal vascularity on Doppler and no fat or solid nodular components — features most consistent with a vascular tumor (haemangioendothelioma) rather than liposarcoma, desmoid, NRSTS or neuroblastoma.

MRI demonstrates fatty atrophy of the abductor digiti minimi with plantar fascia thickening/calcaneal spur consistent with chronic Baxter (inferior calcaneal nerve) entrapment causing ADQ atrophy associated with plantar fasciitis; lack of sensory loss supports motor branch involvement.

CT shows an irregular mass at the 2nd portion of the duodenum/ampullary region with biliary obstruction and multiple hypovascular liver metastases; elevated CA 19-9, weight loss and obstructive jaundice strongly favor an adenocarcinoma (pancreatobiliary/ampullary) rather than inflammation, lymphoma or Crohn's.

Cortical, superficial multicystic 'bubbly' lesion in a child with new-onset seizures, minimal mass effect and only scant enhancement — classic imaging appearance of a dysembryoplastic neuroepithelial tumor (DNET).

Solitary, well-defined posterior paravertebral mass at the lower thoracic level with appearance contiguous to the neural foramen on CT—classic for a neurogenic tumor (eg schwannoma). No history or imaging features to suggest bilateral extramedullary hematopoiesis, lymphoma, Castleman, or esophageal tumor.

MRI and ultrasound show a convoluted tubular multilocular cystic adnexal mass with folded plicae ('cogwheel'/'beads-on-string' appearance) consistent with hydrosalpinx from chronic PID. Clinical course is subacute without fever, arguing against acute tubo-ovarian or other intraabdominal abscess; imaging lacks solid enhancing nodules to suggest cystadenoma/carcinoma.

Contrast-enhanced CT demonstrates high-attenuation pericardial fluid (hemopericardium) with active contrast extravasation from the left ventricular free wall into the pericardial space, consistent with an acute left ventricular free wall rupture causing cardiac tamponade after myocardial infarction.

Pineal region mass in a 43-year-old man with obstructive hydrocephalus, biopsy-proven, showing a solid, relatively homogeneous enhancing lesion with excellent response to radiotherapy. Germinomas are classically radiosensitive in adult males and fit this presentation. Other options (pineoblastoma, dermoid, tectal glioma, meningioma) are less consistent with age, imaging or treatment response.

Multiloculated, predominantly T2-hyperintense cystic lesion at the volar wrist adjacent to the tendon sheath/joint with thin rim enhancement — appearance typical of ganglion cyst. Lack of low-signal hemosiderin/blooming excludes giant-cell tumor of tendon sheath; fibroma of tendon sheath and fibrous lesions are usually solid with low T2 signal or solid enhancement.

CT and US show a well-defined cystic mesenteric mass in the left abdomen with fluid attenuation, thin enhancing wall/septa and surrounding fat stranding and hyperemia on Doppler consistent with infection/inflammation. Imaging pattern (multiloculated/ thin septa, chylous/serous content) and location favor mesenteric cystic lymphangioma complicated by inflammation rather than an enteric duplication (no gut wall signature), pseudocyst (no pancreatitis history), or simple mesothelial cyst.

Adolescent with androgen excess and imaging shows a large mixed solid–cystic adnexal mass; histology images labelled retiform/poorly differentiated match Sertoli‑Leydig cell tumour (androgen‑secreting).

Well-circumscribed submucosal polypoid rectal mass with homogeneous intense enhancement and marked diffusion restriction—findings typical of a rectal carcinoid/neuroendocrine tumour. Lymphoma is usually diffuse/concentric wall thickening; haemangioma is very T2-bright; adenocarcinoma is irregular/infiltrative; GIST is often exophytic/heterogeneous.

CT demonstrates multiple bilateral, small, rounded subcutaneous nodules isodense to fat in buttocks and thighs — pattern typical of injected oil/silicone (oil bubbles/siliconomas) rather than air, neurofibromas, or metastases. Matches reference imaging of self-injected filler.

Well-defined fusiform mass along course of the posterior tibial nerve causing nerve compression; imaging shows ovoid, homogeneous T2-hyperintense, intensely enhancing lesion with internal vascularity and fascicular appearance—features typical of a benign neurogenic tumor (schwannoma) rather than aggressive sarcoma or lymphoma.

Multilobulated left renal mass shows peripheral nodular enhancement in arterial phase with persistent peripheral/target-like enhancement and probable feeding vessel with centripetal fill-in — classic for a vascular haemangioma. Appearance is not typical for abscess (would show thick irregular rim and central pus) or RCC/oncocytoma/angiosarcoma.

Imaging (US and contrast CT) shows a blind-ending, thick-walled fluid-filled tubular structure arising from the distal ileum in the right lower quadrant with surrounding inflammatory fat stranding; ultrasound and surgical specimen are consistent with an inflamed Meckel’s diverticulum that mimicked appendicitis.

Solitary well-circumscribed foraminal/intraforaminal mass displacing nerve roots on axial images, eccentric to the nerve and consistent with a nerve-sheath tumour. Appearance and location favor schwannoma over central/filum-based ependymoma or multifocal drop metastases; neurofibroma is less likely given the eccentric, encapsulated morphology.

Initial WE-CTC showed a short segmental focal narrowing/apparent lesion that completely resolved on the repeated acquisition after further distension/hypotonisation. The transient nature of the finding (no persistent mural thickening, shouldering, or pericolonic changes) is typical of segmental colonic spasm (technical artefact), not carcinoma, diverticulitis, lymphoma or extrinsic compression.

Multiloculated cystic T2-bright mass with multiple vascular septae on Doppler — imaging favors a vascular/cavernous lesion (haemangioendothelioma) rather than solid sarcoma, liposarcoma, desmoid or neuroblastoma.

MRI demonstrates fatty atrophy of the abductor digiti minimi with accompanying plantar fasciitis/calcaneal spur and motor-only symptoms (no sensory loss), consistent with chronic inferior calcaneal (Baxter) nerve entrapment causing ADQ atrophy.

Focal irregular stenosing mass at the ampullary/duodenal region with biliary obstruction and hypodense liver lesions (metastases); clinical obstructive jaundice and elevated CA19-9 favor duodenal/ampullary adenocarcinoma rather than lymphoma which is typically long-segment and homogeneous.

Superficial cortical-based cystic lesion with an enhancing mural nodule in a child presenting with new-onset seizures. The lesion abuts the pia/dura with leptomeningeal contact/possible bone remodeling — classic for pleomorphic xanthoastrocytoma. DNET usually shows no enhancement; ganglioglioma can overlap but PXA’s superficial pial-based cyst + mural nodule is most typical.

Solitary, well-defined posterior paravertebral mediastinal mass in an asymptomatic adult showing homogeneous, avid contrast enhancement on CT — imaging pattern most consistent with unicentric (hyaline-vascular) Castleman disease; neurogenic tumours are common in this location but often show heterogeneous enhancement or foraminal involvement, and other options (lymphoma, EMH, oesophageal tumour) are less likely given solitary hypervascular node-like lesion.

MRI and TVUS show a tubular, multiloculated adnexal mass with high-T2 fluid and intraluminal small mural nodules/beads-on-a-string (mucosal folds), without clinical fever or CT/MR signs of acute inflammation or adjacent bowel disease. These findings are most consistent with chronic hydrosalpinx from prior PID rather than tubo-ovarian abscess, TB, secondary abscess, or ovarian malignancy.

Acute presentation with cardiogenic shock and hyperechoic pericardial effusion; CT shows high‑attenuation pericardial fluid consistent with hemopericardium—findings most consistent with left ventricular free‑wall rupture.
